<ol><li>Make a&nbsp;<b>video clip</b>&nbsp;of a ball's flight after being released from rest.</li><li>A&nbsp;<b>vertical metre rule</b>&nbsp;can be used to provide a scale.</li><li>From the video clip, the <b>time of descent</b> of the ball and the <b>distance fallen</b>&nbsp;by the ball from rest can be measured.</li><li>Since&nbsp;\(s=ut+\dfrac{1}{2}at^2\)&nbsp;and&nbsp;\(u=0\), we have&nbsp;\(s=\dfrac{1}{2}at^2\)</li><li>Plot a graph of&nbsp;\(s\)&nbsp;against&nbsp;\(t^2\), the acceleration is given by&nbsp;\(2\times\text{gradient}\)</li></ol>